"Sakamoto T.T., Hasumi H., Ishii M., Emori S., Suzuki T., Nishimura T., Sumi A.","Responses of the Kuroshio and the Kuroshio extension to global warming in a high-resolution climate model",2005,"Geophysical Research Letters","32","14",,"1","4",,,10.1029/2005GL023384,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-25444434701&partnerID=40&md5=510fbab013cb1177495afa957c8cb8cc","Frontier Research Center for Global Change, Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology, Kanagawa 236-0001, Japan; Center for Climate System Research, University of Tokyo, Chiba 277-8568, Japan; National Institute for Environmental Studies, Ibaraki 305-8506, Japan","Sakamoto, T.T., Frontier Research Center for Global Change, Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology, Kanagawa 236-0001, Japan; Hasumi, H., Center for Climate System Research, University of Tokyo, Chiba 277-8568, Japan; Ishii, M., Frontier Research Center for Global Change, Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology, Kanagawa 236-0001, Japan; Emori, S., Frontier Research Center for Global Change, Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology, Kanagawa 236-0001, Japan, National Institute for Environmental Studies, Ibaraki 305-8506, Japan; Suzuki, T., Frontier Research Center for Global Change, Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology, Kanagawa 236-0001, Japan; Nishimura, T., Frontier Research Center for Global Change, Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology, Kanagawa 236-0001, Japan; Sumi, A., Center for Climate System Research, University of Tokyo, Chiba 277-8568, Japan","Using a high-resolution atmosphere-ocean coupled climate model, responses of the Kuroshio and the Kuroshio Extension (KE) to global warming are investigated. In a climate change experiment with atmospheric CO2 concentration ideally increased by 1% year-1, the current velocity of the Kuroshio and KE increases, while the latitude of the Kuroshio separation to the east of Japan does not change significantly. The increase of the current velocity is up to 0.3 m s-1 at 150°E. This acceleration of the Kuroshio and KE is due to changes in wind stress over the North Pacific and consequent spin-up of the Kuroshio recirculation gyre. The acceleration of the currents may affect sea level along the southern coast of Japan and northward heat transport under global warming. Copyright 2005 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Climatology; Mathematical models; Ocean currents; Sea level; Wind effects; Wind stress; High resolution climate model; Kuroshio Extension (KE); Global warming; climate change; climate modeling; flow velocity; oceanic current; wind stress; Kuroshio Current; oceanic regions; Pacific Ocean; World",,,,,,"Boyer, T.P., (2001) World Ocean Database 2001, Temporal Distribution of Bathythermograph Profiles, 2, p. 119. , [CD-ROM], NOAA Atlas NESDIS 43, NOAA, Silver Spring, Md; Cessi, P., Condie, R.V., Young, W., Dissipative dynamics of western boundary currents (1990) J. Mar. Res., 48, pp. 677-700; Choi, B.-H., Kim, D.-H., Kim, J.-W., Regional responses of climate in the northwestern Pacific Ocean to gradual global warming for a CO2 quadrupling (2002) J. Meteorol. Soc. Jpn., 80, pp. 1427-1442; Cubasch, U., Meehl, G.A., Boer, G.J., Stouffer, R.J., Dix, M., Noda, A., Senior, C.A., Yap, K.S., Projections of future climate change (2001) Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis, pp. 525-582. , edited by J. T. Houghton et al., Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Hanawa, K., Southward penetration of the Oyashio water system and the wintertime condition of midlatitude westerlies over the North Pacific (1995) Bull. Hokkaido Natl. Fish. Res. Inst., 59, pp. 103-119; (2000) Special Report on Emissions Scenarios, p. 612. , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, edited by N. Nakicenovic and R. Swart, Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Ishi, Y., Hanawa, K., Large-scale variabilities of wintertime wind stress curl field in the North Pacific and their relation to atmospheric teleconnection patterns (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett., 32, pp. L10607. , doi:10.1029/2004GL022330; Ishii, M., Kimoto, M., Kachi, M., Historical ocean subsurface temperature analysis with error estimates (2003) Mon. Weather Rev., 131, pp. 51-73; Isobe, A., Imawaki, S., Annual variation of the Kuroshio transport in a two-layer numerical model with a ridge (2002) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 32, pp. 994-1009; K-1 coupled model (MIROC) description (2004), p. 34. , K-1 Model Developers, K-1 Tech. Rep., 1, edited by H. Hasumi and S. Emori, Cent. for Clim. Syst. Res., Univ. of Tokẙo, TokyoKagimoto, T., Yamagata, T., Seasonal transport variations of the Kuroshio: An OGCM simulation (1997) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 27, pp. 403-418; Kawabe, M., Variations of current path, velocity, and volume transport of the Kuroshio in relation with the large meander (1995) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 25, pp. 3103-3117; Lau, N.-C., Nath, M.J., The role of the ""atmospheric bridge"" In linking tropical Pacific ENSO events to extratropical SST anomalies (1996) J. Clim., 9, pp. 2036-2057; Meehl, G.A., Collins, W.D., Boville, B.A., Kiehl, J.T., Wigley, T.M.L., Arblaster, J.M., Response of the NCAR Climate System Model to increased CO2 and the role of physical processes (2000) J. Clim., 13, pp. 1879-1898; Nonaka, M., Xie, S.-P., Covariations of sea surface temperature and wind over the Kuroshio and its extension: Evidence for ocean-to -atmosphere feedback (2003) J. Clim., 16, pp. 1404-1413; Qiu, B., The Kuroshio Extension system: Its large-scale variability and role in the midlatitude ocean-atmosphere interaction (2002) J. Oceanogr., 58, pp. 57-75; Qiu, B., Kuroshio Extension variability and forcing of the Pacific decadal oscillations: Responses and potential feedback (2003) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 33, pp. 2465-2482; Qu, T., Mitsudera, H., Qiu, B., A climatological view of the Kuroshio/Oyashio system east of Japan (2001) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 31, pp. 2575-2589; Schneider, N., Miller, A.J., Pierce, D.